\section{Introduction}

\subsection{The Global Language Barrier in Programming}

Since the inception of computer science, English has maintained an overwhelming dominance as the lingua franca of programming. This dominance extends across every layer of the software development ecosystem: programming language keywords are in English, documentation is predominantly in English, error messages are in English, and technical discussions occur primarily in English. While this standardization has facilitated global collaboration, it has simultaneously created an enormous barrier to entry for the approximately 6 billion people who do not speak English as their first language.

The cognitive overhead of learning programming concepts while simultaneously struggling with a foreign language creates a compounded challenge. Research in educational psychology has consistently demonstrated that learners acquire new concepts more efficiently in their native language. A landmark study by Guzdial and Soloway~\cite{guzdial2002} found that students learning to program in their native language showed significantly higher comprehension rates, better retention, and lower dropout rates compared to those learning in a second language.

\subsection{The Opportunity: 7,000+ Languages, One Framework}

There are approximately 7,000 living languages in the world today, representing an immense reservoir of human cognitive diversity and creative potential. Yet, the programming world remains closed to speakers of most of these languages. Consider the following statistics:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Mandarin Chinese:} 1.1+ billion speakers
    \item \textbf{Spanish:} 500+ million speakers  
    \item \textbf{Arabic:} 400+ million speakers
    \item \textbf{Hindi:} 600+ million speakers
    \item \textbf{Bengali:} 265+ million speakers
    \item \textbf{Portuguese:} 250+ million speakers
    \item \textbf{Russian:} 258+ million speakers
    \item \textbf{Japanese:} 125+ million speakers
\end{itemize}

Collectively, these language communities represent over 4 billion people—more than half of humanity—who face unnecessary barriers when learning to program. Al-Marjaa aims to remove these barriers by providing a universal framework that can be adapted to any language.

\subsection{Vision: Programming in Your Mother Tongue}

The vision underlying Al-Marjaa is simple yet transformative: \textbf{every person should be able to program in their mother tongue}. This vision encompasses two key capabilities:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Native Syntax Programming:} Write code using keywords, identifiers, and syntax that feel natural in your language
    
    \item \textbf{Natural Language Programming (Vibe Coding):} Describe what you want in plain natural language and have executable code generated automatically
\end{enumerate}

This dual approach ensures accessibility at multiple levels: experienced developers can use native syntax for precise control, while beginners and non-programmers can use natural language descriptions to create functional applications.

\subsection{Key Contributions}

This paper makes the following contributions:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Language-Agnostic Architecture:} A modular compiler framework that cleanly separates language-specific components from core infrastructure, enabling adaptation to any human language
    
    \item \textbf{Native-Language Keyword System:} A systematic methodology for defining keywords in any language while maintaining semantic consistency
    
    \item \textbf{Multilingual Vibe Coding:} An AI-powered natural language programming system that works in any supported language
    
    \item \textbf{5-Tier JIT Compilation:} A sophisticated compilation pipeline achieving 5.08x speedup over baseline interpretation
    
    \item \textbf{Comprehensive Evaluation:} Real results from 343 unit tests (99.4\% pass rate) and performance benchmarks up to 19.9M ops/sec
    
    \item \textbf{Open Framework:} Complete documentation and tooling for adapting the framework to new languages
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Paper Organization}

This paper is organized as follows: Section~\ref{sec:related} reviews related work in non-English programming and natural language programming. Section~\ref{sec:architecture} presents the language-agnostic architecture. Section~\ref{sec:multilingual} details the multilingual adaptation methodology. Section~\ref{sec:implementation} describes the implementation. Section~\ref{sec:evaluation} presents evaluation results. Section~\ref{sec:applications} discusses applications. Section~\ref{sec:limitations} addresses limitations. Section~\ref{sec:future} outlines future work. Section~\ref{sec:conclusion} concludes with a call to action.

