\section{Related Work}
\label{sec:related}

\subsection{Non-English Programming Languages}

The concept of programming in languages other than English has been explored across various communities. However, most efforts have been isolated and limited in scope.

\subsubsection{Chinese Programming Languages}

\textbf{Wenyan-lang}~\cite{wenyan2019} represents the most successful attempt at Chinese programming, achieving over 18,000 GitHub stars. It uses Classical Chinese syntax and aesthetics, demonstrating that non-English programming can attract significant community interest. However, Wenyan-lang remains primarily educational, lacking production features like JIT compilation and machine learning integration.

\textbf{Chinese Python} projects have attempted to translate Python keywords to Chinese, but these are typically thin wrappers that don't address the underlying architectural challenges of multilingual programming.

\subsubsection{Japanese Programming Languages}

\textbf{Dolittle} and \textbf{TTSNeo} provide Japanese keywords for educational purposes. These languages have been used successfully in Japanese schools but have not achieved production adoption. They lack modern features such as JIT compilation and integrated AI capabilities.

\subsubsection{Russian Programming Languages}

\textbf{Rapira} was an educational language developed in the Soviet Union. More recently, \textbf{Yargorithm} has attempted to create a Russian-first programming experience. Like other localized languages, these remain limited to educational contexts.

\subsubsection{Arabic Programming Languages}

Previous attempts at Arabic programming include:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Al-Ramz (2008):} Educational language without modern features
    \item \textbf{Qalb (2013):} Interpreted language compiling to JavaScript
    \item \textbf{Arabix (2015):} Conceptual proposal without implementation
\end{itemize}

These efforts shared common limitations: lack of modern compilation, no AI integration, insufficient standard libraries, and—most importantly—no framework for extending to other languages.

\subsection{Natural Language Programming}

\subsubsection{AI-Assisted Code Generation}

Recent advances in large language models have transformed the landscape of code generation. \textbf{GitHub Copilot}~\cite{copilot2021}, based on OpenAI Codex, demonstrates remarkable ability to generate code from English descriptions. However, Copilot primarily operates with English input and generates code in English-based languages.

\textbf{Amazon CodeWhisperer} and \textbf{Google Codey} follow similar patterns, reinforcing English's dominance in the programming world.

\subsubsection{Multilingual NLP Challenges}

Arabic NLP faces unique challenges~\cite{arabicnlp2018} including:

\begin{itemize}
    \item Right-to-left script directionality
    \item Complex morphological system with root-and-pattern derivations
    \item Multiple numeral systems (Eastern and Western Arabic)
    \item Diacritical marks affecting meaning
    \item Dialectal variation across regions
\end{itemize}

These challenges are mirrored in other languages with unique characteristics: Chinese tonal differences, Japanese multiple writing systems, Arabic script variations across languages, and so on. A truly multilingual framework must accommodate all these variations.

\subsection{JIT Compilation Techniques}

Just-In-Time compilation has revolutionized dynamic language performance. Key developments include:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Self (1987):} Pioneered JIT concepts with dynamic optimization
    \item \textbf{HotSpot (1999):} Tiered compilation for Java
    \item \textbf{V8 (2008):} Transformed JavaScript performance
    \item \textbf{PyPy (2011):} Achieved 5-10x speedup for Python~\cite{pypy2011}
    \item \textbf{LuaJIT:} Tracing JIT with exceptional performance
\end{itemize}

Al-Marjaa builds on these techniques while adding optimizations specific to multilingual text processing.

\subsection{What's Missing: A Universal Framework}

No existing system provides a comprehensive framework for adapting programming to any human language. Each effort has been:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Language-specific:} Designed for a single language
    \item \textbf{Educational-only:} Lacking production features
    \item \textbf{Non-extensible:} Hard to adapt to other languages
    \item \textbf{Isolated:} Not part of a larger ecosystem
\end{enumerate}

Al-Marjaa addresses all these gaps by providing a universal, extensible, production-ready framework.

