\section{Language-Agnostic Architecture}
\label{sec:architecture}

The key innovation of Al-Marjaa is its language-agnostic architecture. Unlike previous localized programming languages that hard-coded language-specific elements throughout their codebases, Al-Marjaa cleanly separates concerns into two distinct layers:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Language-Independent Core:} Compiler infrastructure, optimization passes, runtime system
    \item \textbf{Language-Specific Layer:} Keywords, syntax rules, error messages, NLP models
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Architectural Overview}

Figure~\ref{fig:architecture} illustrates the complete architecture:

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Architecture Layers and Components}
\label{fig:architecture}
\begin{tabular}{@{}p{3.5cm}p{3.5cm}p{5cm}@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Layer} & \textbf{Component} & \textbf{Description} \\
\midrule
\multirow{4}{*}{\textbf{Language Layer}} 
 & Keyword Definitions & Native-language tokens \\
 & Syntax Rules & Language-specific grammar \\
 & Error Messages & Localized diagnostics \\
 & NLP Models & Language-specific AI \\
\midrule
\multirow{5}{*}{\textbf{Core Layer}} 
 & Lexer Engine & Unicode-aware tokenizer \\
 & Parser Generator & Grammar-agnostic parser \\
 & AST Optimizer & Language-independent passes \\
 & Bytecode Compiler & Target-agnostic compilation \\
 & JIT Compiler & 5-tier optimization \\
 & Virtual Machine & Stack-based execution \\
\midrule
\multirow{3}{*}{\textbf{Runtime Layer}} 
 & Standard Library & Localized APIs \\
 & ONNX Runtime & ML model execution \\
 & UI Framework & RTL/LTR-aware components \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\subsection{The Separation Principle}

The fundamental principle underlying Al-Marjaa's architecture is: \textbf{Language-specific components should be configuration, not code}. This principle manifests in several ways:

\subsubsection{Keyword Definitions as Data}

Keywords are defined in external configuration files, not hard-coded in the compiler:

\begin{lstlisting}[caption={Keyword Configuration Example}]
// arabic_keywords.yaml
keywords:
  variable: "متغير"
  function: "دالة"
  class: "صنف"
  if: "إذا"
  else: "وإلا"
  for_each: "لكل"
  while: "بينما"
  return: "أرجع"
\end{lstlisting}

\begin{lstlisting}[caption={Chinese Keyword Configuration}]
// chinese_keywords.yaml
keywords:
  variable: "变量"
  function: "函数"
  class: "类"
  if: "如果"
  else: "否则"
  for_each: "对于每个"
  while: "当"
  return: "返回"
\end{lstlisting}

\begin{lstlisting}[caption={Spanish Keyword Configuration}]
// spanish_keywords.yaml
keywords:
  variable: "variable"
  funcion: "funcion"
  clase: "clase"
  si: "si"
  sino: "sino"
  para_cada: "para_cada"
  mientras: "mientras"
  retornar: "retornar"
\end{lstlisting}

\subsubsection{Syntax Rules as Grammar Specifications}

Syntax rules are expressed in a meta-language that can be adapted:

\begin{lstlisting}[caption={Grammar Specification}]
// grammar_spec.yaml
rules:
  function_declaration:
    pattern: "{function_keyword} {name}({params}) {body}"
    example_ar: "دالة جمع(أ، ب) { أرجع أ + ب؛ }"
    example_zh: "函数 加(甲, 乙) { 返回 甲 + 乙; }"
    example_es: "funcion sumar(a, b) { retornar a + b; }"
\end{lstlisting}

\subsubsection{Error Messages with Localization}

Error messages support multiple languages through a localization system:

\begin{lstlisting}[caption={Error Message Localization}]
// errors.yaml
errors:
  undefined_variable:
    en: "Undefined variable: {name}"
    ar: "متغير غير معرف: {name}"
    zh: "未定义的变量: {name}"
    es: "Variable no definida: {name}"
    ru: "Неопределенная переменная: {name}"
\end{lstlisting}

\subsection{The Universal Core}

The language-independent core provides all compilation and execution services:

\subsubsection{Lexer Engine}

The lexer is designed to handle:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Unicode Text:} Full UTF-8 support for any script
    \item \textbf{RTL/LTR Detection:} Automatic text direction handling
    \item \textbf{Script Recognition:} Identifying character sets (Arabic, CJK, Cyrillic, etc.)
    \item \textbf{Number Formats:} Multiple numeral systems (Arabic, Persian, Western, Chinese)
    \item \textbf{Punctuation Variants:} Language-specific punctuation marks
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Parser Generator}

The parser uses a grammar-agnostic approach:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Recursive Descent:} Clean, maintainable parsing
    \item \textbf{Error Recovery:} Graceful handling of syntax errors
    \item \textbf{AST Normalization:} Produces language-independent AST
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Optimization Pipeline}

The optimizer applies language-independent transformations:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Constant Folding:} Evaluate constant expressions at compile time
    \item \textbf{Dead Code Elimination:} Remove unreachable code
    \item \textbf{Strength Reduction:} Replace expensive operations with cheaper ones
    \item \textbf{Inline Expansion:} Inline small functions
    \item \textbf{Loop Optimization:} Hoist invariants, unroll loops
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{JIT Compilation System}

The 5-tier JIT compiler adapts to runtime behavior:

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{JIT Compilation Tiers}
\label{tab:jit}
\begin{tabular}{@{}clll@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Tier} & \textbf{Threshold} & \textbf{Optimizations} & \textbf{Target} \\
\midrule
0 & 0 executions & Interpretation & One-time code \\
1 & 50 executions & Direct threading & Warm code \\
2 & 200 executions & Basic optimization & Hot code \\
3 & 1,000 executions & SIMD vectorization & Very hot code \\
4 & 5,000 executions & Tracing JIT & Critical paths \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Key JIT features:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Hot Spot Detection:} Automatic identification of frequently executed code
    \item \textbf{Speculative Optimization:} Optimize based on observed types
    \item \textbf{Deoptimization:} Graceful fallback when assumptions fail
    \item \textbf{SIMD Utilization:} Vectorized operations for numerical code
\end{itemize}

