\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}

\subsection{Summary of Contributions}

Al-Marjaa represents a paradigm shift in programming language design. By creating a truly language-agnostic framework, we have demonstrated that:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Native-language programming is practical:} The framework achieves production-ready performance with 99.4\% test pass rate and 5.08x JIT speedup.
    
    \item \textbf{Any language can be supported:} The modular architecture enables adaptation to any human language with minimal effort—days, not months.
    
    \item \textbf{Natural language programming works:} Vibe Coding enables programming through natural language descriptions in any supported language.
    
    \item \textbf{The architecture is extensible:} New languages, features, and optimizations can be added without modifying core components.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{A Call to Action}

We envision a future where:

\textarabic{كُلُّ شَخصٍ يَقدِرُ عَلى البَرمَجَة بِلُغَتِهِ الأُمّ، يُعَبِّرُ عَن أَفكارِهِ بِشَكلٍ طَبيعيّ، ويُساهِمُ في البِناءِ الرَّقمِيّ لِمُجتَمَعِه.}

\textbf{Every person can program in their mother tongue, express their ideas naturally, and contribute to the digital development of their community.}

Chinese: 每个人都能用母语编程，自然地表达想法，为社区的数字化发展做出贡献。

Spanish: Cada persona puede programar en su lengua materna, expresar sus ideas naturalmente y contribuir al desarrollo digital de su comunidad.

Russian: Каждый человек может программировать на родном языке, естественным образом выражать свои идеи и вносить вклад в цифровое развитие своего сообщества.

\subsection{Opening the Door}

By open-sourcing Al-Marjaa, we are opening a door that has been closed since the beginning of computing: the door to programming in one's own language. We invite:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Language Communities} to adapt Al-Marjaa to their languages
    \item \textbf{Educators} to use Al-Marjaa in their classrooms
    \item \textbf{Researchers} to study the effects of native-language programming
    \item \textbf{Developers} to contribute to the framework and build upon it
    \item \textbf{Organizations} to adopt Al-Marjaa for their needs
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Final Thoughts}

The dominance of English in programming was never a technical necessity—it was a historical accident. Al-Marjaa proves that we can build programming systems that respect and celebrate linguistic diversity. By doing so, we unlock the creative potential of billions of people who have been excluded from full participation in the digital revolution.

\textarabic{لُغةُ المَرجِع لَيسَت مُجَرَّد لُغةِ بَرمَجة، بَل هِيَ حَرَكَةٌ نَحو عالَمٍ أَكثَر شُمولِيَّة، حَيثُ التِّقنَةُ خِدمَةٌ لِلجَميع، لا امتِيازٍ لِلقَلَّة.}

Al-Marjaa is not just a programming language—it is a movement toward a more inclusive world, where technology serves everyone, not just a privileged few.

